Viewing data

Ive downloaded a small set of data from the International Atomic Energy Agency Global Network for Isotopes in Precipitation that includes water isotope data collected in the last 10 years from 14 sites around the world. With this data source, I cant pull directly, but I can convert and load a .csv. The code chunk that produces this table also cleans up the data for display. The GNIP source doesnt specify units (!!) so I have had to guess.

Basic ggplots

Here is a basic ggplot for water isotopes, with the code to generate it:

theme_set(theme_tufte(base_family = "Helvetica"))

axis.x.label <- expression(paste(delta^{18}, "O ( VSMOW)"))
axis.y.label <- expression(paste(delta, "D ( VSMOW)"))

plot.MWL <- ggplot() +
  
  # plot features
  geom_point(data=waters.all %>%
               drop_na(O18, H2), 
             aes(x=O18, y=H2, color=Country), size = 1) +
  geom_abline(data=NULL, aes(slope=8, intercept=10, shape="GMWL")) +
  
  # legend 
  scale_color_colorblind() + 
    # without any adjustments to the legend, this one is haphazard 
  
  # axes and titles
  coord_cartesian() + 
  labs(x = axis.x.label, 
       y = axis.y.label,
       caption = "Global Meteoric Water Line shown in black")

plot(plot.MWL)

This plot shows time series data. The code is hidden, it is very similar to the above, with the addition of a copy of the data set for time series analysis.

Next, Id like to plot different variables over time. This could be accomplished with a function that builds ggplots from input variables, but here is where Ill try something new with Shiny. Rendering this .Rmd notebook and building with the two ggplots above is already affecting Hugo performance, so I imagine Shiny will as well.
